Want to use node.js to build large scale, real-time, enterprise applications?

object.content:
Want to use node.js to build large scale, real-time, enterprise applications? 

I am currently looking for smart driven engineers to add to my amazingly talented team. Sound interesting? Shoot me an email at scott.rahner@dowjones.com. If you just like the idea or have friends that might be interested please +1 or re-share!

Dow Jones has to deliver all the latest news and market data in real time to our customers and we are using node.js to do it. We are rewriting, or have already released, almost every major application in node.js. We have a homegrown framework that we needs your help to evolve. Doing this for 2+ years in production puts us way ahead of the curve. You can have it all: working for one of the most successful media companies in history while getting the technology, practices, and culture of a startup. #nodejs   #coding   #jobs   #career   #programming   #programmer   #mongodb

items.annotation: Want to work with Node.js all day and have the stability of a company that just celebrated its 131st birthday? Join us at Dow Jones.

object.content:
*Look* (https://github.com/baryshev/look) for Node.js
1. Transaction monitoring,  2. CPU profiler,  3. Memory profiler

Look is a tool for performance profiling. It's based on nodetime, but runs completely locally on your server.

Just npm install look and require('look').start() to start it.

items.title: Today, I opened my email and saw a pretty clever technique used in a marketing email. It was from OfficeMax...

object.content:
Today, I opened my email and saw a pretty clever technique used in a marketing email. It was from OfficeMax, and had a perfectly working countdown timer (below) that was counting the exact time to their 6pm sale.

It's an email, thus—no JS; so how did they do it?

Well, it looks like the request to the image is actually to a service, which generates an animated png, starting with the current time, and counting down to the time of the sale. Neat, right?

Want Google without the input field? 

In the screenshots below, on the left you see the new Google, with a single search input field, provided by Chrome's omnibox (Chrome beta channel); nice and simple. On the right you see the same page, but in (Full Screen) Presentation Mode, which I often use for complete hacker-news... ahem... research paper immersion. Note that the input field is again missing. items.title: He'll make you laugh; he'll make you think. If you haven't already, do yourself a favor and watch Dan...

object.content:
He'll make you laugh; he'll make you think. If you haven't already, do yourself a favor and watch Dan Ariely's short talks on human behavior; they're super-insightful and entertaining.

And if you've already listened to the talks, and are hungry for more, he published three great books.

attachments.content: It's become increasingly obvious that the dismal science of economics is not as firmly grounded in actual behavior as was once supposed. In "Predictably Irrational," Dan Ariely tells us why.

items.title: A bit ago, +Douglas Crockford proposed and then implemented contextual function nesting-level coloring...

object.content:
A bit ago, +Douglas Crockford proposed and then implemented contextual function nesting-level coloring of JS. (G+ thread: goo.gl/GAQUl) 

Just yesterday, +Daniel Lamb posted his demonstration of the technique.
http://daniellmb.github.io/JavaScript-Scope-Context-Coloring/example/scope-coloring.html#fullmonad

I like the idea, in some cases, especially in refactors or code navigation, seeing highlighting for scopes makes more sense than the pieces of syntax. I think I'd probably toggle back and forth.

(Looks like +Antony Scriven is working on vim integration as well)
